"Everyone will soon be able to be identified, anywhere and at any time," said Justin Brookman, who is responsible for the privacy of consumers within the Center for Democracy and Technology (CDT) in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism in one, and pessimism in another?
Biometry will be based on new techniques, which will provide new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most used biometric data are fingerprints, the contour of the hand and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its own constraints.
"For example, some people working on concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are unlegible," says Philippe Robin, technical director of the identity domain at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection as well as the verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand assume a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
It is both a safety - we cannot capture this data without their knowledge - and a disadvantage: the procedure must sometimes be repeated and therefore takes time.
As a result, research has been carried out over the past 20 years on other approaches, such as the recognition of the face or iris (the colourful part of the eye).
As a result of increased sensor accuracy and computer computing capacity for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has been multiplied by ten over the past five years, calculates Cyrille Bataller, Director of Accenture R & D Laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the United Kingdom and Holland have deployed automatic border posts using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
"Today we are conducting research on voice recognition or how to walk with sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment," says Sridhar Iyengar, Director of Security Research at Intel Labs.
As a unique and infalsifiable marker, DNA is also a source of hope and concern.
"In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered the ultimate biometric data," Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Prospective at CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers the judicial police a suitcase of 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples at the crime scene in one hour.
The uses of biometrics are divided into two groups: identification (recognizing one person among others) and authentication (ensuring that the person is the person she claims to be).
The identification was so far concerned with the issue of identity documents: biometric elements (prints, photos, iris) must be confronted with the information that the State has on all the citizens already stranded.
This makes sure that a person does not try to usurp someone else's identity.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC thus offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or store.
"We are recovering images from surveillance cameras and comparing them to photos of celebrities that circulate freely on the Internet," explains Dany Nassif, who is responsible for NEC France's commercial development for biometric identification solutions.
Another use is to photograph a quidam in a store, to track its progression through facial recognition and to calculate the waiting time.
The authentication initially concerned physical access (borders, protected premises, canteens...) or logical access (computer opening).
In addition, more recently, the presence control.
"A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of a boyfriend who points for another," explains Cyrille Bataller of Accenture.
But, increasingly, authentication will also concern transactions, particularly those made from Internet-connected devices.
In Japan, it is already possible to remove money from some distributors by introducing his card and placing his hand on a biometric player: this gesture replaces the secret code hit.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by Natural Security in partnership with banks and large distribution signs: when paying in store with its bank card, the client does not tape his code, but introduces his finger into a player that scans his veins.
The experiment is planned for six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French merchants.
Trails to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometrics attractive to the general public.
The first is to explain that she can save time.
"If, thanks to biometrics, a client remains in cash 30 seconds less, it is appreciable," says the director of a large surface.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you customized options.
And, finally, reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect databases.
"The fingerprints are stored on a first server; people's identities are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure case, which blokes if we try to move it," says Philippe Robin of Thales.
But, because of the lack of extensive studies, it is impossible to know whether these speeches really convince users.
Privacy specialists continue to be concerned.
"The progress of facial recognition, the multiplication of surveillance cameras and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa, make me fear the worst: widespread surveillance," predicts Andrew Patrick, of the Office of the Privacy Commissioner in Canada.
