Scientists have just highlighted how a dog's tail movements are linked to his mood.
Previous studies had revealed that happy dogs were more stirring their tail to the right (from the dog's point of view), while nervous dogs were stirring it more to the left.
But now scientists say that dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Thirty, said: "Everyone knows that in man, the left and right side of the brain are involved in different ways in stimuli that awaken positive or negative emotions."
Here we tried to see what was in other species.
He added that as well as in humans, in dogs the right side of the brain was responsible for movement to the left and vice versa, and that both hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the disorderly tail movements of other dogs, researchers followed animals watching films with other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of animals and analysed their behaviour.
It will probably not take long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes on one side and sometimes on the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: "We have presented to dogs films with other dogs - either a naturalist version or a silhouette to avoid any other confusion factor - and we have been able to track the tail movement and present it as going more left or right."
When the animals saw a dog without expression stirring the tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog who stirred the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they found a dick deflected mainly to the left (again from the point of view of the retreat dog), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he didn't think the dogs were deliberately communicating with each other through these movements.
He rather thinks that dogs know from experience what movements they should or should not worry about.
He added: "If you meet other dogs several times and you notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tail to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and that the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will reactivate according to this experience."
Researchers indicate that the results could allow owners, veterinarians and dressers to better understand the emotions of their animals.
Canin Behaviour Expert John Bradshaw, a guest professor at the School of Veterinary Sciences at the University of Bristol, stated that this was not the first study to examine the importance of the left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team from Lincoln University discovered that the dogs were turning their heads to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a happy dog.
And in another scientific study conducted by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: "Dogs are going more easily to a robot dog when his tail is moving to the left rather than to the right, rather than becoming anxious - the opposite of what is in the Italian study."
He indicated that differences could come from the fact that the dogs who participated in the various studies did not fully consider the animals of the films or the robots dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could be useful, he explained.
"Although many elements, found in different mammals, indicate that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be specified - and dogs are no exception," he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviour can be recorded, it will certainly not take long before we understand why their tail sometimes moves on one side and sometimes on the other.
