A team of biologists led by the Wildlife Conservation Society in New York identified a new species of bosse dolphin off the northern coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, responsible for the scientific mission to the Observatory for the Conservation and Study of Animals and Milieux Marins (OCEAMM) returns to L'Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identifying new species.
You're surprised about the discovery of this new bosse dolphin?
It's good news, but I'm not particularly surprised.
If in the past, species have been described and identified on a morphological, anatomical and geographical basis, today, the development of new tools such as genetics allows us to improve our knowledge in species classification sciences.
It is not impossible for these advances in genetics and molecular biology to question the classification or membership of a species in a genus, family or even order.
In the early 19th century, morphologists classified animals based on morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these rankings are being challenged due to advances in genetics.
In the same way, two very close morphologically species have been distinguished through genetics.
This is the case with the new species that has just been identified.
About ten years ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: Pacific Booster Dolphins and Atlantic Booster Whales.
The recent analyses have made it possible to distinguish four species.
Why is this an important discovery, as the Wildlife Conservation Society said?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences, in order to protect the species and therefore its genetic variability.
If this population was already known for a long time by the researchers, they did not know that it was part of a new species, present only in this place.
Therefore, if a problem of mass mortality caused by a viral epidemic or accidental capture occurs in the region, we could deal with the extinction of a species, rather than the local disappearance of a population of a species that is more widely known on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered to be threatened or endangered by the number of individuals on Earth, that is, the stock, and the potential for recovery from neighbouring stocks.
As for the Sousa chinensis species, whose population of the new species was discovered, its stock automatically became lower, making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats where there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This gene brewing limits the creation of new species.
On the other hand, more closed ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can eventually lead to the creation of new species.
It must be known that the marine environment is the least well-known environment.
We'd rather send robots to Mars, than know what lives in the Mariana pit, just 11 kilometres from the sea surface.
We spend more money in the search for life on other planets than in marine research and it is high time that it changes.
