Vote here or via your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the 10 CNN Heroes of the year 2013.
You can vote for him, or one of the other 10 heroes, to elect him "CNN Heroes of the Year."
This person will receive $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his sick father alternately times of consciousness and unconsciousness and went to hospitals that were not equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he had only one broken arm, but he contracted an infection that spread to his brain, creating a hematoma whose sequelae he was going to wear the rest of his life.
"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon," said Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him abroad if we had had enough money.
Instead, Dr. Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to clinics and bonded hospitals, so that he could get any treatment he could receive.
"It's not easy," says Bwelle.
You can leave the house at 5: 00, ruin you at the hospital to be the first, and you're not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
People can die because they wait too long.
The situation has not changed much since Dr. Bwelle's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon there is only one doctor per 5,000 inhabitants, according to the World Health Organization.
As a comparison, the United States ratio is 1 doctor per 413 inhabitants.
And even if they could see a doctor, many Camerounais could not pay for the consultation.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and almost three quarters of the country's health expenditure is made in the private sector.
"The only problem they have is poverty," said Dr. Bwelle.
And because of poverty, they cannot enjoy life.
After seeing his father and so many of his compatriots suffer, Dr. Bwelle was determined to try to change the course of things.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers have carried out more than 700 free surgical acts over the past year.
He became a doctor himself, working as a vascular surgeon at Yaoundé Central Hospital.
And he set up a non-profit humanitarian association, ASCOVIME, which goes to rural areas during the weekends to provide free health care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have helped close to 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, with about 30 people, they get into vans after setting the medical equipment on the roof and cross difficult land to go to villages that need most help.
Lucky doesn't always follow them.
They have had to push vehicles many times to cross rivers or slopes.
But when they arrive, they are received as heroes: the community organizes a party, singing and dancing and offers them the best available accommodation.
In these villages, free health care is a good reason to celebrate, and Dr. Bwelle - with his great smile and overwhelming energy - is more than happy to join the festivities.
The next morning, the team began to receive hundreds of patients.
"We receive 500 people at each visit," said Mr. Bwelle.
They sometimes live 60 km from the village, and they come on foot.
In this travelling hospital, various health care is provided.
Many people receive treatment against malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, pests and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others can receive crutches, a pair of collected glasses or a free birth certificate - a document necessary to go to school, but many poor families simply cannot afford to buy it.
In the evening, the team practice simple surgical acts under local anesthesia.
The operations are usually carried out in a school, city hall or house; after the intervention, the patient rises and goes to the awakening room to leave his place to the next person.
Through the lighting of the generator, the operating room and the sterilization of the equipment, Dr. Bwelle and his volunteers work until the first hours of Sunday morning.
This is an awful rhythm, but village musicians generally help the team to remain motivated.
"They hit drums all night to keep us awake so we can continue to work," Bwelle said.
On Sunday, the team returned to the city, tired but proud of the work it had done.
The group, made up of Cambodian doctors and medical students, has carried out 700 surgical acts free of charge over the past year, and it knows that their presence can make all the difference for those to whom they help.
One man explained that the free operation he had suffered to treat a hernia would allow him to work again.
"This will change my future and that of my family," the man said.
In addition to making this travelling hospital live and working as a surgeon at the hospital, Dr. Bwelle also works at night in private medical firms around Yaoundé.
It is this second job, he explains, which funds 60% of its association; the rest is covered by private donations.
"I don't know when he sleeps," said Katie O'Malley, a second-year medical student from Drexel University in Philadelphia and a volunteer in Dr. Bwelle's group.
He's still in the hospital or trying to find money for his association in order to be able to conduct these campaigns.
For medical students and nursing students such as Katie O'Malley, who come from the United States and Europe to join Mr. Bwelle in his missions, this is a field learning opportunity that they do not have at home.
"We were able to take part in operations to help spill the blood or hand over the instruments to Dr. Bwelle," said Ms. O'Malley.
This is not something you have the opportunity to do in America when you are a second-year medical student.
Volunteer students generally pay their travel to Cameroon, and often arrive with medical equipment collected.
But once in Yaoundé, their pension, their transport and education are taken care of by Dr. Bwelle.
"He's a hero, there's no doubt," Katie O'Malley said.
He gives his life for this association, and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is not near to extinguishing.
For Dr. Bwelle, the relatively constant workload is not a challenge.
Helping others live happy keeping the promise he made to his father is something that brings him an immense joy.
"I'm so happy when I do this job," Bwelle added.
And I'm thinking about my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
Smiling people and relieving pain are the reasons why I do this.
